XV

1. multa nefanda: contrary to the Latin idiom Sallust sometimes omits the conjunction after multa, when joined to another attributive.

2. sacerdote Vestae : her name was Fabia and she was the sister· in-law of Cicero, She was acquitted of the crime here mentioned, in 73 a. e., but as Sallust repeats the charge he seems to have thought her guilty.

3. ius fasque: the first crime violated the human law of society, the second was also an insult to the goddess ; hence sas is added.

⁶. illi: dative with nubere-dubitabat: when this verb means to hesitate, it usually takes the infinitive (ἓ 76).

7. aetate: ablat. of specification (ἓ 39).—creditur . . . fecisse: as captus shows, the writer intended to use the personal construction . with creditur, but substituted the impersonal bythe addition of pro certo without, however, altering captus to coptum. Such an incongruity is called anacoluthon (change of grammatical construction).

8. nuptiis: dative of purpose (5 30).
